{"title_page": "North Lanarkshire", "text_new": "{{short description|Council area of Scotland}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = North Lanarkshire<br/>''{{lang|sco|North Lanrikshire}}''<br/>''{{lang|gd|Siorrachd Lannraig a Tuath}}''\n| official_name           =\n| native_name             = <!-- if different from the English name -->\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| other_name              =\n| image_skyline           = [[File:North Lanarkshire in Scotland.svg|250px]]\n| image_flag              = \n| image_shield            = North lanarkshire arms.jpg\n| image_blank_emblem      = northlanarkshirelogo.png\n| blank_emblem_type       = \n| image_map               = \n| map_caption             = \n| coordinates = {{coord|55.829|N|3.922|W|type:adm2nd_region:GB|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| seat_type               = Admin HQ\n| seat                    = [[Motherwell]]\n| government_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| governing_body          = North Lanarkshire Council\n| leader_title            = Control\n| leader_name             = [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]] minority (council [[No overall control|NOC]])  <!-- North Lanarkshire -->\n| leader_title1           = [[List of MPs for constituencies in Scotland (2019-present)|MPs]]\n| leader_name1            = * [[Steven Bonnar]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill (UK Parliament constituency)|Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill]])\n* [[Marion Fellows]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Motherwell and Wishaw (UK Parliament constituency)|Motherwell and Wishaw]])\n* [[Neil Gray]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Airdrie and Shotts (UK Parliament constituency)|Airdrie and Shotts]])\n* [[Stuart McDonald (Scottish politician)|Stuart McDonald]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East (UK Parliament constituency)|Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East]])\n| leader_title2           = [[Members of the 5th Scottish Parliament|MSPs]]\n| leader_name2            = * [[Jamie Hepburn]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Cumbernauld and Kilsyth]])\n* [[Richard Lyle]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Uddingston and Bellshill (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Uddingston and Bellshill]])\n* [[Alex Neil (politician)|Alex Neil]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Airdrie and Shotts (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Airdrie and Shotts]])\n* [[Clare Adamson]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Motherwell and Wishaw (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Motherwell and Wishaw]])\n* [[Fulton MacGregor]] ([[Scottish National Party|SNP]], [[Coatbridge and Chryston (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Coatbridge and Chryston]])\n| unit_pref               = Imperial\n| area_footnotes          = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_total_km2          = {{Scottish council populations|ARE=S12000044}} \n| area_rank               = [[List of Scottish council areas by area|Ranked {{Scottish council populations|ARK=S12000044}}]]\n| population_footnotes    = <!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| population_total        = {{Scottish council populations|POP=S12000044 }}\n| population_as_of        = {{United Kingdom statistics year|Scotland}}\n| population_rank         = [[List of Scottish council areas by population|Ranked {{Scottish council populations|RNK=S12000044}}]]\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| area_code_type          = [[ONS coding system|ONS code]]\n| area_code               = S12000044\n| iso_code                = GB-NLK\n| website                 = {{URL|http://www.northlanarkshire.gov.uk/}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''North Lanarkshire''' ({{lang-gd|Siorrachd Lannraig a Tuath}}) is one of 32 [[council areas of Scotland|council areas]] of [[Scotland]]. It borders the northeast of the [[City of Glasgow]] and contains many of Glasgow's suburbs and [[commuter town]]s and villages. It also borders [[East Dunbartonshire]], [[Falkirk (council area)|Falkirk]], [[Stirling (council area)|Stirling]], [[South Lanarkshire]] and [[West Lothian]]. The council covers parts of the [[shires of Scotland|traditional counties]] of [[Dunbartonshire]], [[Lanarkshire]] and [[Stirlingshire]].\n\nThe area was formed in 1996, from the districts (within [[Strathclyde]] region) of [[Cumbernauld and Kilsyth]], [[Motherwell (district)|Motherwell]], and [[Monklands (district)|Monklands]], as well as part of the [[Strathkelvin]] district ([[Chryston]] and [[Auchinloch]]), which operated between 1975 and 1996. As a new single-tier authority, North Lanarkshire became responsible for all functions previously performed by both the regional council and the district councils.\n\n==History==\nThe largest part of North Lanarkshire, in the south of the county, has its roots in the [[Shires of Scotland|history county]] of [[Lanarkshire]], which has existed since around the time of King [[David I of Scotland|David I]], who ruled Scotland from 1124 to 1153.<ref name=\"LanarkshireBrit\">{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Lanarkshire |work=Encyclopaedia Britannica |title=Lanarkshire |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The county was based around the town of [[Lanark]], now in [[South Lanarkshire]], which had been the site of the first [[Parliament of Scotland]] under [[Kenneth II of Scotland|Kenneth II]] in 978, and was granted [[burgh]] status by David in 1140.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.southlanarkshire.gov.uk/info/200165/local_and_family_history/618/lanark_from_kings_to_covenanters |accessdate=30 March 2020 |title=Lanark from kings to covenanters |work=South Lanarkshire}}</ref> The northern parts of North Lanarkshire were in the historic counties of [[Dunbartonshire]] and [[Stirlingshire]].<ref name=\"NorthLanarkshireBrit\">{{cite web |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/North-Lanarkshire |work=Encyclopaedia Britannica |title=North Lanarkshire |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> The area now covered by North Lanarkshire has five historical burghs: [[Airdrie, North Lanarkshire|Airdrie]], [[Coatbridge]], [[Kilsyth]], [[Motherwell]] and [[Wishaw]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.northlanarkshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=34171 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |title=Common Good Register |work=North Lanarkshire}}</ref> The population of North Lanarkshire grew quickly during the [[Industrial Revolution]]. In the 18th century the county's towns, including Motherwell, were active in textile production. The discovery of coal and iron ore deposits in the 19th century, as well as the building of the Glasgow to Edinburgh railway, transformed the region.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://culturenl.co.uk/museums/steeling-back-memories-ravenscraig/history-of-motherwell/ |work=Culture NL |accessdate=30 March 2020 |title=History of Motherwell}}</ref> The towns of Motherwell, Coatbridge and Wishaw became centres of the iron and steel industry. These industries began to decline in the second half of the 20th century, while a growth occurred in the financial and technology sectors, as well as a growth in logistics services related to the heavy goods traffic in the area. The [[New towns in the United Kingdom|new town]] of [[Cumbernauld]] expanded rapidly after [[World War II]], and is now the largest town in North Lanarkshire. The growth of the [[Greater Glasgow]] metropolitan area into the south-western part of the county has also led to a large number of residential areas for commuters.<ref name=\"NorthLanarkshireBrit\"/>\n\nThe North Lanarkshire county area was established in 1996 as part of [[1990s United Kingdom local government reform|a reorganisation of local government]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.scot/policies/local-government/ |work=Scottish Government |accessdate=30 March 2020 |title=Policy: Local government}}</ref> This was the latest in a series of reforms, starting [[Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889|in 1889]] with the establishment of a county council for Lanarkshire in 1889 and followed [[Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973|in 1975]] by the abolition of the county and its absorption into the larger [[Strathclyde Region]].<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=Scottish Parliament |url=http://www.parliament.scot/Research%20briefings%20and%20fact%20sheets/SB07-31.pdf |title=Local Government \u2013 Subject Profile |author=Stephen Herbert |date=13 June 2007}}</ref> The 1996 reform abolished Strathclyde, and established North Lanarkshire as a merger of the districts of [[Cumbernauld and Kilsyth]], [[Monklands (district)|Monklands]], [[Motherwell (district)|Motherwell]] and four of the wards of [[Strathkelvin]] district.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=North Lanarkshire |url=https://mars.northlanarkshire.gov.uk/egenda/images/att60125.pdf |date=March 1995 |title=Joint Working Group Report: Planning and Development}}</ref>\n\n==Geography and demographics==\nNorth Lanarkshire lies in the [[Central Lowlands|Central Valley]] of Scotland, to the east of [[Glasgow]]. It lies on the Scotland's north\u2013south [[drainage divide|watershed]] with the [[River Clyde]] flowing through the west of the county on its way to the [[Irish Sea]], and the [[River Almond, Lothian|River Almond]] in the east emptying into the [[Firth of Forth]] near Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.northlanarkshire.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=6193&p=0 |work=North Lanarkshire |title=North Lanarkshire State of the Environment Report |date=December 2005 |accessdate=30 March 2020 |p=43}}</ref> The northern areas consist of forests as well as higher areas such as the [[Kilsyth Hills]].<ref name=\"NorthLanarkshireBrit\"/>\n\nThe highest population density of North Lanarkshire is in the urbanised south-west, which is part of the [[Greater Glasgow]] metropolitan area. Northern and eastern areas are more rural in character, with agricultural activity such as dairy and meat farming.<ref name=\"NorthLanarkshireBrit\"/> The largest towns in North Lanarkshire are [[Cumbernauld]], which in 2008 had a population of 51,610, followed by [[Coatbridge]] (43,970), [[Airdrie, North Lanarkshire|Airdrie]] (37,130), and [[Motherwell]] (32,120).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.undiscoveredscotland.co.uk/usscotfax/geography/townscities.html |work=Undiscovered Scotland |title=SCOTTISH CITIES & TOWNS BY POPULATION |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Wards==\n[[File:Motherwell Civic Centre - geograph.org.uk - 3045184.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Motherwell Civic Centre]], headquarters of North Lanarkshire Council, located in [[Motherwell]]]]\nThe council is made up of 21 wards,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.northlanarkshire.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=33038 |title=2017 Wards: Boundaries, population and household numbers|publisher=North Lanarkshire Council |year=2018 |accessdate=8 February 2019 }}</ref> as follows:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ward Number\n! Ward Name\n! 2017 Population\n|-\n|1\n|Kilsyth\n|11,832\n|-\n|2\n|Cumbernauld North\n|19,670\n|-\n|3\n|Cumbernauld South\n|16,206\n|-\n|4\n|Cumbernauld East\n|16,608\n|-\n|5\n|Stepps, Chryston and Muirhead\n|11,623\n|-\n|6\n|Gartcosh, Glenboig and Moodiesburn\n|13,438\n|-\n|7\n|Coatbridge North\n|15,320\n|-\n|8\n|Airdrie North\n|20,062\n|-\n|9\n|Airdrie Central\n|16,570\n|-\n|10\n|Coatbridge West\n|14,213\n|-\n|11\n|Coatbridge South\n|17,286\n|-\n|12\n|Airdrie South\n|19,803\n|-\n|13\n|Fortissat\n|15,706\n|-\n|14\n|Thorniewood\n|13,916\n|-\n|15\n|Bellshill\n|15,252\n|-\n|16\n|Mossend and Holytown\n|12,799\n|-\n|17\n|Motherwell West\n|14,129\n|-\n|18\n|Motherwell North\n|18,667\n|-\n|19\n|Motherwell South East and Ravenscraig\n|20,146\n|-\n|20\n|Murdostoun\n|18,489\n|-\n|21\n|Wishaw\n|18,225\n|-\n|\n|Overall Total\n|339,960\n|}\n\n==Politics and governance==\n===Political composition===\n{{see also|:Category:North Lanarkshire 